This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

Put this code in a .NET 9/C#13 console app and launch in debug mode:

```cs
using System.Collections.ObjectModel;
using System.Diagnostics;

var names1 = GetNames1();
var names2 = GetNames2();
Debugger.Break();
static IReadOnlyCollection<string> GetNames1() => ["Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"];
static IReadOnlyCollection<string> GetNames2() => new ReadOnlyCollection<string>(["Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"]);
```

The QoL difference between debugging `names1` and `names2` is tremendous:

![grafik](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4ee5d3fa-ba6d-44d9-8a7c-e15f55b33833)
![grafik](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a57d0094-4975-4732-bd1a-79275153b78d)

It's because `names1` is a compiler-generated type without any debugger support, while `ReadOnlyCollection` for `names2` and similar classes all feature amenity attributes like

```cs
[DebuggerTypeProxy(typeof(ICollectionDebugView<>))]
[DebuggerDisplay("Count = {Count}")]
```

Can the compiler-generated class for `IReadOnlyCollection<T>` and `IReadOnlyList<T>` collection expressions get support for a prettified debug view, too?

_Originally posted by @LWChris in https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/discussions/78632_

**Version Used**: .NET SDK 9.0.203, C# language version 13.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Create a .NET class library project (or compile/analyze this code with your own means, while showing warnings)
2. Create a non-nullable `IEnumerable<T>` object of any `T` type or size (a derivative like `T[]` or `List<T>` can also be used)
3. Reference that object using a redundant null conditional operator (i.e. `obj?.ToString()`)
4. Reference that object without using a null conditional operator (i.e. `obj.ToString()`)

**Diagnostic Id**: `CS8602: Dereference of a possibly null reference.`

**Expected Behavior**: CS8602 should not be raised in this scenario.

**Actual Behavior**: CS8602 is raised in this scenario.

**Example Code**:
```csharp
namespace shutupcompiler;

public class Class1
{
    public static void DoSomething()
    {
        // With a non-nullable array, implying that it is nullable
        // will cause the code after to result in null reference warnings:
        object[] nonNullableArr = []; // Create an array with zero elements
                                      // (the way it is created is irrelevant)

        // These alternative construction methods still don't change the analysis/output either:
        // object[] nonNullableArr = new object[0];
        // Or the following grotesque method will still not change the analysis
        // object[] nonNullableArr = [.. new object().GetType().Assembly.CustomAttributes.Where(_ => false).Cast<object>()];
        nonNullableArr?.ToString(); // This implies arr is a nullable type, though it is not.
        nonNullableArr.ToString();  // CS8602: Dereference of a possibly null reference.
                                    // Despite arr's target type not being nullable,
                                    // this erroneous warning will appear.

        // With a blank slate:
        object[] anotherArr = nonNullableArr;
        anotherArr.ToString();      // An object reference to the same array with
                                    // the same action does not cause the warning.

        // This error only manifests with strictly IEnumerable<T>.
    }
}
```

Many other similar issues pertaining to this issue might come from the same underlying issue, but those show a bug that occurs on a **nullable** object of any type (or a specific type). This bug occurs specifically in **non-nullable** `IEnumerable<T>` and derived types.

