> Using `VisualStudio.17.Preview/17.14.0-pre.7.0+36109.1` targeting `net10.0`.
> 
> If an `enum` is marked with `[Flags]` it makes no sense to enforce populating a switch expression. What should it be populated with anyway? All permutations? All values?
> 
> ### Example
> namespace EnumWarning;
> 
> internal class Program
> {
>     [Flags]
>     enum Foo
>     {
>         None,
>         A = 1,
>         B = 2,
>         C = 4
>     }
> 
>     static void Main(string[] args) => Console.WriteLine(Bar(Foo.A));
> 
>     private static string Bar(Foo a)
>     {
>         return a switch // IDE0072
>         {
>             Foo.A | Foo.B => "A or B",
>             Foo.C => "C",
>             _ => ""
>         };
>     }
> }
> To begin with, it makes no sense to produce IDE0072 if there is a default case like above. But it certainly gets worse when dealing with a `Flags` enum, since it by nature could have billions of values.

